# API Validation — Postman MCP

> **Primary flow:** `01-orchestrator.mdc` — this file runs only for **Phase 3** when classification is **API** or **Both**.

---

## PHASE 3-B — API Validation

### Step 1: Identify Collection and Environment

Check the ticket description and labels for any mention of a Postman collection or target environment.

If either is unclear or not mentioned, ask the user before proceeding.

If the Postman MCP returns a **finite list** of collections or environments, show each as a **numbered line**; the user replies with the number(s). Otherwise use:

```
Before API validation, I need:

Collection: [which Postman collection?]
Environment: [DEV / QA / Staging / …]

```

Then present the choice using the **`AskQuestion` tool**:

- **id:** `api-collection-env`
- **prompt:** “How would you like to provide the collection and environment?”
- **options:**
  - `reply` — “I'll reply with collection name + environment in my next message”
  - `list` — “List available collections/environments from Postman (if MCP supports it)”

Wait until you have both collection and environment (by number pick or explicit names). Do not proceed to any API fetch or call without both confirmed.

---

### Step 2: Fetch API Details from Postman

Using the Postman MCP, fetch:
- The specified collection
- The relevant endpoint(s) related to the bug described in the ticket
- For each endpoint, extract:
  - Full URL (with environment base URL applied)
  - HTTP Method
  - Request Headers
  - Request Body / Query Parameters
  - Authentication type and token location

---

### Step 3: Consolidate P1 Test Cases

If the ticket requires validation of multiple endpoints or scenarios, identify and present only **P1 (Primary / Critical) cases** — the minimum set that directly validates the bug fix.

```
=== P1 TEST CASES FOR VALIDATION ===

  Case 1: [Test Case Name]
    Endpoint: [METHOD] [Full URL]
    Purpose:  [What this validates in relation to the bug]

  Case 2: [Test Case Name]
    Endpoint: [METHOD] [Full URL]
    Purpose:  [What this validates in relation to the bug]

(Non-P1 cases have been excluded from this validation run.)

```

Then present the choice using the **`AskQuestion` tool**:

- **id:** `api-p1-confirm`
- **prompt:** “Proceed with these P1 test cases or correct?”
- **options:**
  - `proceed` — “Proceed with these P1 cases”
  - `correct` — “I will correct the case list (reply with changes)”

Do not proceed until the user selects **proceed** (or sends an unambiguous **CONFIRM**).

---

### Step 4: Confirm Full Request Details Per Case

For each confirmed test case, present the complete request details for user review before executing:

```
=== API CALL CONFIRMATION — Case [N]: [Test Case Name] ===

Method:       [GET / POST / PUT / PATCH / DELETE]
URL:          [Full resolved URL]
Environment:  [ENV Name]
Headers:      [Key: Value]
              [Key: Value]
Payload:      [Request body or query params — formatted clearly]
Auth:         [Auth type — Bearer Token / API Key / Basic Auth / None]
              [Token source — e.g., "token to be provided by user" or "pulled from Postman env variable"]

If auth credentials are needed, ask for them in the same turn or before execution.

```

Then present the choice using the **`AskQuestion` tool**:

- **id:** `api-call-confirm`
- **prompt:** “Execute this API call or correct the request?”
- **options:**
  - `execute` — “Execute this call”
  - `correct` — “I will correct the request (reply with changes)”

- If credentials or tokens are required and not available in the Postman environment, ask the user to supply them explicitly at this step.
- Never assume or fabricate auth tokens.

---

### Step 5: Execute API Calls

Execute each confirmed call directly using the Postman MCP or direct API call — no scripting.

For each call, display the **full response immediately** after execution so the user can review it:

```
=== RESPONSE: Case [N] — [Test Case Name] ===

Status Code:    [e.g., 200 OK / 400 Bad Request / 401 Unauthorized / 500 Internal Server Error]
Response Time:  [ms]
Response Body:
{
  [Full response body displayed here — do not truncate]
}

Observation: [Agent's interpretation — does this response indicate the bug is fixed? Note any unexpected fields, status codes, or error messages.]

```

Then present the choice using the **`AskQuestion` tool**:

- **id:** `api-response-review`
- **prompt:** “Continue to the next case or stop to discuss?”
- **options:**
  - `continue` — “Continue to next case”
  - `stop` — “Stop here (discuss this response)”

If the user selected **one-at-a-time** review at the start of Step 5, after each response wait until they pick **continue** or **stop** before the next call. If they chose **run-all**, skip the per-response `AskQuestion` prompt until the final summary (or only on error).

Clarify review preference at the start of Step 5 (before the first execution):

Present the choice using the **`AskQuestion` tool**:

- **id:** `api-review-preference`
- **prompt:** “How would you like to review API responses?”
- **options:**
  - `one-at-a-time` — “Show each response one at a time — wait for my reply before the next call”
  - `run-all` — “Run all cases — show the full summary at the end”

---

### Step 6: Handle Errors, Blocks, and Missing Verdicts During Execution

#### Blocked before a pass/fail verdict

If you **cannot execute** a P1 case or **cannot interpret** the response in relation to the bug **yet** — e.g. Postman MCP unavailable, collection/env missing, auth token absent, **401/403 before any business response**, connection refused, wrong base URL, prerequisite call not done:

- **Do not** conclude that the bug **passed** or **failed** — treat as **indeterminate / blocked** until a valid validation response exists.
- State which **validation point** was not reached (which case, which endpoint, what was missing).
- **Ask the user how to resolve the block** so execution can reach that point (supply env, token, collection name, VPN, order of calls, etc.). Wait for explicit direction; do not fabricate secrets.

#### Unexpected errors after a call is executed

If an API call returns an unexpected error (e.g., 500, connection refused, auth failure, timeout) **and** you still cannot judge the bug fix from the outcome:

1. **Stop execution of remaining cases.**
2. Report the error clearly:
   ```
   ❌ Case [N] Error
   Endpoint: [METHOD] [URL]
   Status:   [Code + message]
   Body:     [Error response body]
   Likely Cause: [e.g., Invalid auth token / Environment URL misconfigured / Endpoint not deployed to this env]
   ```
3. Ask how to proceed using the **`AskQuestion` tool**. If the error means **no pass/fail verdict** is possible yet, say so and prioritize options that **unblock** the validation point:

   - **id:** `api-error-action`
   - **prompt:** “Case [N] failed. How would you like to proceed?”
   - **options:**
     - `retry` — “Retry with corrected parameters (I'll provide details)”
     - `skip` — “Skip this case and continue”
     - `abort` — “Abort API validation”

> ⚠️ Also refer to `self-improvement-api.mdc` — if the error was caused by a faulty guideline in this file, update that file after resolving the issue.

---

### Step 7: API Validation Summary

After all cases are executed and reviewed, present the consolidated results:

```
=== API VALIDATION RESULTS ===

Environment: [ENV Name]

✅ / ❌  Case 1: [Name] — [METHOD] [URL] — Status [code] — [Pass / Fail]
✅ / ❌  Case 2: [Name] — [METHOD] [URL] — Status [code] — [Pass / Fail]

Overall Result: PASS ✅ / FAIL ❌ / Incomplete — blocked (no pass-fail verdict) 🔶
```

If the run ended **blocked** before a verdict on the bug, use **Incomplete — blocked** and describe what the user must supply to proceed — **do not** draft Jira wording that asserts the bug passed or failed until validation completes.

Return this result summary to `01-orchestrator.mdc` for use in the Jira comment draft.

---

## Postman MCP Tool Reference

| Tool | When to Use |
|---|---|
| Fetch collection | Retrieve all endpoints in a named Postman collection |
| Fetch environment | Retrieve base URLs and env variables for a named environment |
| Execute request | Run a specific request from a collection against a target environment |

---

## Guardrails

- Never generate API test scripts, code, or automation files of any kind.
- Never execute an API call before the user has confirmed the full request details.
- Never fabricate or assume auth tokens — always ask the user if credentials are missing.
- Always display the full response body — do not truncate or summarise it.
- Always stop and report on error — never silently skip a failed call.
- Limit test cases to P1 scope only — do not expand without explicit user instruction.
- If the Postman MCP is unavailable, report it immediately and halt — do not attempt workarounds.
- If blocked before a validation verdict, ask the user how to resolve the block; do not assert PASS/FAIL for the bug.
